    name: 'RAG (Retrieval-Augmented Generation)',
    category: 'AI Explained',
    subcategory: 'Generative AI',
    definition: 'Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) is an AI architecture that enhances language model outputs by retrieving relevant information from a knowledge base before generating a response. Instead of relying solely on the model internal parameters, RAG first queries a vector database or search index for documents related to the user query, then feeds that retrieved context to the LLM alongside the original question. This grounds the model response in verifiable, up-to-date information, significantly reducing hallucinations and enabling access to private or proprietary data.',
    simpleExplanation: 'RAG is like giving a student an open-book exam. Instead of answering from memory alone which might be wrong, the student can look up relevant passages in a textbook and use them to formulate a correct, well-sourced answer.',
