    id: 'ai-14',
    slug: 'transformer-architecture',
    name: 'Transformer Architecture',
    category: 'AI Explained',
    subcategory: 'Neural Networks',
    definition: 'The Transformer is a neural network architecture introduced in the seminal 2017 paper Attention Is All You Need. It revolutionized AI by replacing recurrent layers RNNs with a self-attention mechanism that processes all tokens in a sequence simultaneously rather than sequentially. This parallelization enables vastly more efficient training on modern hardware. The Transformer consists of an encoder and decoder composed of layers of multi-head self-attention and feed-forward neural networks. It is the foundation of virtually all modern LLMs including GPT, BERT, Gemini, and Claude.',
    simpleExplanation: 'The Transformer is like a team of experts reading a document together. Instead of reading word-by-word like RNNs, every expert reads every word simultaneously and they communicate about which words are most important. This parallel approach is faster and captures context better.',
    example: 'Google Translate uses Transformer architecture. When translating The bank of the river was beautiful, self-attention helps the model understand that bank means riverbank not financial bank by attending to the words river and beautiful.',
    whyItMatters: 'The Transformer is arguably the most important AI innovation of the past decade. It enabled scaling language models from millions to trillions of parameters, made training dramatically faster through parallelization, and unlocked capabilities like reasoning and code generation.',
    formula: 'Attention(Q, K, V) = softmax(Q * K^T / sqrt(d_k)) * V',
    formulaDescription: 'The self-attention formula computes how much each token should attend to every other token. Q query, K key, and V value are matrices from input embeddings. The dot product QK^T measures similarity between tokens scaled by 1/sqrt(d_k) for numerical stability.',
    relatedTerms: ['large-language-model', 'neural-network', 'deep-learning', 'natural-language-processing', 'embeddings'],
    interviewQuestions: ['Explain the self-attention mechanism and why it is better than recurrence.', 'What is multi-head attention and why is it beneficial?', 'How does positional encoding work in Transformers?', 'What is the difference between encoder-only, decoder-only, and encoder-decoder Transformer architectures?', 'How does the Transformer architecture scale with model size?'],
    commonMistakes: ['Confusing attention with understanding attention weights show what the model looks at not what it understands.', 'Thinking Transformers have no position information they use positional encodings to track word order.', 'Underestimating the quadratic complexity self-attention is O(n^2) in sequence length making long contexts expensive.'],
    sharkTankExample: 'A startup pitches a Transformer-based model optimized for legal document analysis using sparse attention patterns to handle 200,000+ token documents efficiently.',
    realCompanyExample: 'GitHub Copilot uses a Transformer-based model Codex to suggest code. The Transformer processes code context variable names, functions, comments and predicts what code should come next.',
    visualDiagram: 'Input Sequence -> Token Embeddings + Positional Encoding -> Multi-Head Self-Attention -> Add and Normalize -> Feed-Forward Network -> Add and Normalize repeated N layers -> Output Sequence',
    quickSummary: 'The Transformer is a neural network architecture based on self-attention that processes all input tokens in parallel. Introduced in 2017, it replaced RNNs and became the foundation for LLMs like GPT, BERT, and Claude.',
    faqs: [
      { question: 'Why is it called Transformer?', answer: 'The name comes from the architecture ability to transform one sequence into another. The original paper focused on translation but the architecture proved universally powerful.' },
      { question: 'What is the difference between BERT and GPT architectures?', answer: 'BERT is encoder-only reading bidirectionally ideal for understanding tasks classification, QA, NER. GPT is decoder-only reading left-to-right ideal for generation tasks.' },
      { question: 'How do Transformers handle long documents?', answer: 'Standard self-attention is O(n^2). Efficient variants address this: Longformer uses sparse attention, Reformer uses locality-sensitive hashing, and FlashAttention optimizes GPU implementation.' },
      { question: 'Why does the Transformer need positional encoding?', answer: 'Self-attention processes all tokens simultaneously and has no notion of sequence order. Positional encodings add position information allowing the model to use word order.' },
      { question: 'What is multi-head attention?', answer: 'Instead of computing one attention score per token pair, multi-head attention runs multiple parallel operations typically 8-96 heads. Each head learns different relationships.' },
    ],
