    id: 'ai-15',
    slug: 'tokenization',
    name: 'Tokenization',
    category: 'AI Explained',
    subcategory: 'LLM Fundamentals',
    definition: 'Tokenization is the process of converting raw text into smaller units called tokens that an AI model can process. For modern language models, tokens are typically subwords pieces of words that balance vocabulary size with information preservation. The tokenizer uses algorithms like Byte-Pair Encoding BPE to split text: common words become single tokens like the or cat, while rare words break into multiple tokens. Each token is mapped to a unique numerical ID in the model vocabulary.',
    simpleExplanation: 'Tokenization is like cutting a pizza into slices before eating. The pizza is your text and tokens are the slices. Some slices are big common words, some are small uncommon words. The total number of slices determines your context budget.',
    example: 'In GPT-4 tokenizer, the word hello is one token, the sentence Hello how are you today is about 6 tokens, and antidisestablishment is 5 tokens. Cost and context limits are based on token count not word count.',
    whyItMatters: 'Tokenization affects everything in LLM applications: cost APIs charge per token, context window capacity, processing speed, and multilingual capability. Poor tokenization degrades model performance and increases costs.',
    formula: 'V = {t1, t2, ..., tN}, Tokenize(s) = [id(ti) for ti in BPE(s)]',
    formulaDescription: 'The vocabulary V is a set of N tokens learned during tokenizer training. BPE Byte-Pair Encoding splits input text s into tokens by iteratively merging the most frequent pairs. Each token is converted to a numerical ID.',
    relatedTerms: ['large-language-model', 'embeddings', 'transformer-architecture', 'natural-language-processing'],
    interviewQuestions: ['How does Byte-Pair Encoding BPE tokenization work?', 'Why do different languages tokenize differently and why does that matter?', 'How does tokenization affect context window usage?', 'What problems can occur with tokenization in code generation?', 'Compare WordPiece, BPE, and SentencePiece tokenization algorithms.'],
    commonMistakes: ['Counting words instead of tokens 75 words is about 100 tokens for English but ratios differ by language.', 'Assuming special tokens do not matter every API call, system prompt, and formatting character consumes token budget.', 'Not considering tokenization for non-English text some languages require 2-3x more tokens than English.'],
    sharkTankExample: 'A startup pitches a token optimizer that rewrites prompts to use fewer tokens while preserving meaning. For a company processing 1M queries/month, reducing average token count by 30% saves hundreds of thousands in API costs.',
    realCompanyExample: 'OpenAI charges per token for input and output. A customer service chatbot processing 100M tokens/month at $0.01 per 1K tokens pays $1,000/month just in API costs. Tokenization directly impacts bottom line.',
    visualDiagram: 'Raw Text: I love machine learning -> Byte-Pair Encoding Tokenizer -> Tokens: I, love, machine, learning, ! -> Token IDs: 40, 789, 1523, 4567, 0 -> Model Input',
    quickSummary: 'Tokenization breaks text into subword units that AI models process. It affects cost, context limits, and model performance. Different tokenizers and languages have vastly different token-to-word ratios.',
    faqs: [
      { question: 'How many tokens are in a typical word?', answer: 'In English, one word averages about 1.3-1.5 tokens. Common words like the or is are 1 token. Longer or rarer words break into multiple tokens. Code and math tokenize less efficiently.' },
      { question: 'Can I choose my own tokenizer?', answer: 'If training your own model, yes you can train a BPE tokenizer on domain data. If using existing models like GPT-4 or Claude, you use their fixed tokenizer.' },
      { question: 'How does tokenization handle numbers?', answer: 'Numbers are tokenized character by character or in small groups. 123456 might become 12, 34, 56. This is why LLMs sometimes struggle with arithmetic the tokenization breaks numeric patterns.' },
      { question: 'What is the difference between tokenization in English vs Chinese?', answer: 'Chinese text tokenizes very differently because characters carry more meaning. A 100-character Chinese text might use 50-80 tokens while the same meaning in English uses 50-60 tokens.' },
      { question: 'Why does hello and Hello both need 1 token?', answer: 'Most tokenizers are case-sensitive and have separate entries for hello and Hello as well as HELLO, hello!, and hello-world if they appear frequently enough in training.' },
    ],
