    name: 'Reinforcement Learning',
    category: 'AI Explained',
    subcategory: 'Core Concepts',
    definition: 'Reinforcement Learning RL is a machine learning paradigm where an agent learns to make decisions by interacting with an environment, receiving rewards or penalties, and learning to maximize cumulative reward over time. Unlike supervised learning which learns from labeled examples or unsupervised learning which finds patterns, RL learns from trial and error. The agent explores actions, observes outcomes, and gradually learns optimal behavior. RL powers game-playing AlphaGo, robotics, and fine-tunes LLMs through RLHF.',
    simpleExplanation: 'Reinforcement learning is like training a dog with treats. The dog tries different behaviors and gets a treat when it does the right thing. Over time the dog learns which actions get treats. The AI does the same trying actions and getting rewards.',
    example: 'DeepMind AlphaGo used RL to master Go. Initially it played randomly and lost. Through millions of self-play games it learned which moves led to winning and which led to losing. It eventually defeated the world champion.',
    whyItMatters: 'RL is the only ML paradigm that learns from interaction rather than static data making it essential for sequential decision-making. It powers robotics, game AI, autonomous driving, and aligns LLMs through RLHF.',
