    subcategory: 'Core Concepts',
    definition: 'Unsupervised learning is a machine learning paradigm where models find patterns, structures, or relationships in data without any labeled examples or pre-defined categories. The algorithm must make sense of the data on its own discovering clusters, reducing dimensionality, identifying anomalies, or learning the underlying distribution. Without right answers to guide it, unsupervised learning reveals hidden structures that humans may not have known to look for. Key techniques include clustering, dimensionality reduction, and anomaly detection.',
    simpleExplanation: 'Unsupervised learning is like sorting a pile of mixed Lego bricks without instructions. You do not have labels, you naturally group them by color, size, and shape discovering categories yourself. The AI does the same finding hidden patterns.',
